	abstract = {We study star formation over 12 Gyr using pop-cosmos, a generative model trained on 26-band photometry of 420,000 COSMOS2020 galaxies (IRAC Ch.1 \${\textless}26\$). The model learns distributions over 16 SPS parameters via score-based diffusion, matching observed colours and magnitudes. We compute the star formation rate density (SFRD) to \$z=3.5\$ by directly integrating individual galaxy SFRs. The SFRD peaks at \$z=1.3{\textbackslash}pm0.1\$, with peak value \$0.08{\textbackslash}pm0.01\$ M\$\_\{{\textbackslash}odot\}\$ yr\${\textasciicircum}\{-1\}\$ Mpc\${\textasciicircum}\{-3\}\$. We classify star-forming (SF) and quiescent (Q) galaxies using specific SFR \${\textless}10{\textasciicircum}\{-11\}\$ yr\${\textasciicircum}\{-1\}\$, comparing with \$NUVrJ\$ colour selection. The sSFR criterion yields up to 20\% smaller quiescent fractions across \$0{\textless}z{\textless}3.5\$, with \$NUVrJ\$-selected samples contaminated by galaxies with sSFR up to \$10{\textasciicircum}\{-9\}\$ yr\${\textasciicircum}\{-1\}\$. Our sSFR-selected stellar mass function shows a negligible number density of low-mass (\${\textless}10{\textasciicircum}\{9.5\}\$ M\$\_{\textbackslash}odot\$) Q galaxies at \$z{\textbackslash}sim1\$, where colour-selection shows a prominent increase. Non-parametric star formation histories around the SFRD peak reveal distinct patterns: SF galaxies show gradually decreasing SFR correlations with lookback time (\$r{\textbackslash}sim1\$ to \$r{\textbackslash}sim0\$ over 13 Gyr), implying increasingly stochastic star formation toward early epochs. Q galaxies exhibit full correlation (\$r{\textgreater}0.95\$) during the most recent \${\textbackslash}sim\$300 Myr, then sharp decorrelation with earlier star-forming epochs, marking clear quenching transitions. Massive (\$10{\textless}{\textbackslash}log\_\{10\}(M\_*/\$M\$\_\{{\textbackslash}odot\}){\textless}11\$) galaxies quench on a time-scale of \${\textbackslash}sim1\$ Gyr, with mass assembly concentrated in their first 3.5 Gyr. Finally, AGN activity (infrared luminosity) peaks as massive (\${\textbackslash}sim10{\textasciicircum}\{10.5\}\$ M\$\_{\textbackslash}odot\$) galaxies approach the transition between star-forming and quiescent states, declining sharply once quiescence is established. This provides evidence that AGN feedback operates in a critical regime during the \${\textbackslash}sim1\$ Gyr quenching transition.},
